<date>1561813554686< /date><rating>5</rating>< text>
There are only a hand full of places to eat in Arnold. This would be my first choice to eat and it's kid friendly. I give this round table a 5 star because it earned it. The place is always clean and the pizza is good, never really greasy. They have plenty of seating along with a area for the little ones to play viedo games. They have about 4 tvs and they always have sorts on so if tour into sports you can't go wrong. The employees walk around and ask of you need anything and is everything ok. That's cool because other round tables don't do that. Bathrooms are clean so that's always a plus for me too.< /text>

<Rate>5<//Rate><text>I had a baby in February at the new maternity wing of the Memorial Hospital. We signed up for their maternity tour and got a full tour of the wing and the new rooms before hand. It was very clean, neat and tidy. When it came time for me to have my son, I had to have a c-section. All the nurses and staff were very helpful and kind. They went over every step of the procedure with me and my husband. They even told me what was happening step by step as the operation was going on. Letting me know what they were doing, what I should or should not be feeling and they let my husband stay in the room and hold my hand. After, I got a private room for my whole stay, with my own bathroom. All the rooms are now private. The room had a couch for my husband to sleep on, so he could be in the room with me at night. The staff was very friendly, caring and didn't try to rush us out like some hospitals. They even encouraged me to stay an extra day when I said I wanted to go home. (I had to stay 4 days) They wanted to make sure my baby and I were both recovering well before leaving. Over the past six years I've been a patient at CMHS for multiple in-patient and out-patient surgeries. I had one week-long stay. I've had tests, procedures, therapy in nearly every department including the Cancer Center across the street. I've also accompanied folks to the emergency room on a few occaisions - in both the old and new facilities. All of this is just to say that I'm fairly familiar with the hospital and have interacted with so many employees. So very rarely, I've encountered someone who isn't having a great day. But 99.9% of the time the people who've helped me have been stellar. Kind, caring, attentive, easy-going, encouraging. I don't know how they do it. Keep this up while helping people through some very intense, uncomfortable, awkward, painful, scary situations. Reading each patient to gauge their needs. I feel well cared for here. I feel lucky to have CMH right here.< /text>

<UserId.>116245894067354866731<//UserId.><Name>Seth Long< /Name><date>1397775773248<//date><Rate>1< /Rate>< text>
On 4/15/2014, I took my 4-year-old son, who was in severe respiratory distress, to the ER. When I arrived in the ER nobody was at the reception window. I knocked on the glass, as I could see people back there, but nobody came to help. I found a security guard who was able to help direct me to a receptionist. The receptionist took my insurance info and told me to wait in the waiting room for the triage nurse to call us. I reiterated to her the urgency of my son's condition.

We waited nearly 30 minutes, with my son struggling to breath, but the triage nurse still hadn't called us. I got up to complain and afterwards just decided we'd be better off going to Ventura County Medical Center a few blocks away. When we arrived there, my son was quickly evaluated by the triage nurse, immediately taken back and treated by the doctor, and eventually admitted to the hospital.

Community Memorial Hospital jeopardized the health and well-being of my child by failing to provide adequate and timely care. I worked for many years on an ambulance and certainly understand that hospitals can get crowded, but waiting 30+ minutes just to be seen by the triage nurse is not acceptable and jeopardizes lives. They need to get their act together.</text>

I ordered the Chilaquiles with Green Tomatillo Sauce, Grilled Chicken, Over-Hard Eggs, Guacamole, and Sour Cream with a side order of Refried Beans. I also had the mixed Pineapple-Mango Agua Fresca. Their Agua Frescas is so good and refreshing with chunky bits of fruits "just the way I like it".

< rating>
4< /rating>
<Text>Kaboom!  Guess who stepped in the room?  Kapow!

One of Earth's greatest joys to me is the taste of Thai cuisine.  Hungry for pad kee mao (drunken noodles),  I remembered the often overlooked by me, Kapow Thai restaurant, which is an eatery I always seem to pass by as I go to & fro the city of Cypress.

The restaurant has an extensive menu of authentic Thai dishes, which include lunch & dinner specials that come with rice & soup.

Thai tea-
Kapow's Thai tea is brewed in-house, making for a more assertive flavor.  The thing I appreciate most is it's subtle sweetness, since I try not to consume too much sugar when possible.

Pad kee mao (Drunken noodles w/beef, heat level:medium)-
With spicy fat rice noodles, stir fried together with mint leaves, green onions, tomato, bell pepper, chili & choice of beef, the pad kee mao was tantalizing & pressing all my happy buttons.  The portion was filling, the taste sensational & the heat (with the addition of chili paste & spiced vinegar) just the right amount to induce perspiration w/o numbing the tastebuds.  One of the signature items on the menu, do get this when you get the chance!

Service was great!  Al runs the family-owned & operated restaurant, after taking over for his dad who had medical issues.  We shot the breeze over things such as his dislike for durian, squid & other food items which I happen to enjoy.  Al modernized Kapow by adding  online ordering.  I'm sure his dad must be very proud of what his son has accomplished in his absence.

A good amount of seating, with tables & booths.  Don't expect a fancy, hoity toity ambiance to Kapow.  It's a casual, welcoming place to share a meal.  Parking is in a private lot, shared by Aki Sushi, Tambuli market and other businesses.

I got Kapow'd right in da tummy!  The pad kee mao at Kapow was delicious & really hit the spot.  Eating exotic Thai cuisine, all while supporting a wonderful family business are why I highly suggest checking out Kapow the next time you crave noodles or some other Thai dish.  I left full & happy.

Highly recommend!
NOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOM< /Text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

Its been more than couple of months since i have been to this place owing to mostly the erratic timings during afternoon. Google claims that this place is open at 11 while twice i went there and it was closed and there were few unfortunate patrons wondering what happened as they came to the place based on recommendations.

Nevertheless, i went there at 12:30 PM and still the lunch buffet was not kept there. when it was served, i noticed that chicken tikka was cold while the veg samosa and seekh kebab was missing.
I was told that veg samosa is served only during specials and seekh kebab will take some time. Kebab didnt even made it to the table till i was almost full. The same rice has chicken, goat and veg pieces placed in to make it three types of biryani. Also, the same cold chicken tikka was in the gravy to term it as chicken tikka masala. I wish i can give 1 star but i will give 2 just because of the decent goat biryani. Definitely not worth $13 plus taxes and tip.</text>

Food is quite good. Pricing is about standard for good Indian/Pakistani restaurants. Appears to be a Mom & Pop shop.

The bread and Garlic naan in particular is quite superb. Lovely big pieces that are just delightful. Mango Lassi was very generous.

Would recommend checking this place out.<//Text>
